6":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"před 28. ledna 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13. června 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, Anglie","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Anglie","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"1596–1624":"1596–1624","1556–1627":"1556–1627","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1624":"1624","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"før 28. januar 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13. juni 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"nl":{"1596–1624":"1596–1624","1556–1627":"1556–1627","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1624":"1624","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"vóór 28 januari 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13 juni 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"en":{"1596–1624":"1596–1624","1556–1627":"1556–1627","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1624":"1624","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"before 28 January 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13 June 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dunn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinn</b>, <b>Ó Doinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘brown-haired’ or ‘chieftain’. Compare   Dunne  . This name has sometimes been Anglicized as   Brown  .","English: nickname for a dark complexioned or swarthy man, from Middle English <i>dun</i> ‘dun, dark’ (Old English <i>dunn</i> ‘dull brown’).","Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus, named with Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘fort’. Compare   Dun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Cahal, Eamonn, Grainne.","Chinese: variant of   Dunn  .","German (<b>Dünne</b>): nickname for a slender, skinny person, from Middle High German <i>dünne</i> ‘thin’."]},{"name":"Brown","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: generally a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion, Middle English <i>br(o)un</i>, from Old English <i>brūn</i> or Old French <i>brun</i>. This word is occasionally found in Old French, Middle English and Old Norse as a personal name or byname (Middle English personal name <i>Brun</i>, <i>Broun</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Bruno</i>, Old English <i>Brūn</i>, or possibly Old Norse <i>Brúnn</i> or <i>Brúni</i>). <i>Brun-</i> was also an ancient Germanic name-forming element. Some instances of Old English <i>Brūn</i> as a personal name may therefore be short forms of compound names such as <i>Brūngar</i>, <i>Brūnwine</i>, etc. As a Scottish and Irish name, it sometimes represents a translation of Gaelic <i>Donn</i> (see below). <i>Brown</i> (including in the senses below) is the fourth most frequent surname in the US. It is also very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below).","Irish and Scottish: adopted for <b>Ó Duinn</b> (see   Dunn  ) or for any of the many Irish and Scottish Gaelic names containing the element <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ (also meaning ‘chieftain’), for example   Donahue  .","Irish: phonetic Anglicization of <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhnaigh</b>; see   Breheny  ."]},{"name":"Don","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Agustin, Jose, Miguel, Pablo, Ramon, Ruben, Adriana, Ausencio, Eduardo, Enrique, Erasmo, Francisco.","English and Scottish: variant of   Dunn  .","English and Scottish: variant of   Dun  , a habitational name from Dun in Angus, Scotland."]},{"name":"Done","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alfredo, Angel, Berto, Cristobal, Dinora, Eloisa, Francisco, Generoso, Gustavo, Juan.","English: variant of <b>Donne</b>, itself a variant of   Dunn  ."]},{"name":"Dunsford","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dunsford in Devon, from the genitive case of the Old English personal name <i>Dunn</i> (see   Dunn  ) + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. Although Dunsforth in Yorkshire also gave rise to the surname, it appears not to have survived the medieval period."]},{"name":"Dunford","meanings":["habitational name from Dunford Bridge, in Thurlstone (Yorkshire), so called from the river <i>Don</i> (a British name possibly meaning ‘river’) + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, or from Dunford House in Methley (Yorkshire), named in Old English as ‘Dunn's ford’ (see   Dunn   2).","variant of <b>Durnford</b>, a habitational name from Durnford in Wiltshire, arising from Old English <i>dierne</i> + <i>ford</i> ‘hidden ford’. Alternatively, the name may perhaps arise from Dunford, alias Durnford, in Addlestone (Surrey).","English:"]},{"name":"Donn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Chaim, Isaak, Meyer, Zorach.","English (Lancashire) and Scottish (Caithness): variant of   Dunn  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Don  ."]},{"name":"Dunson","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a patronymic from   Dunn   2 or4. Compare   Donson  ."]},{"name":"Dun","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus.","English: variant of   Dunn  .","Dutch: nickname from Middle Dutch <i>dun</i> ‘thin’."]}]},{"name":"Margareta","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margarete","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margrethe","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705210,"age":4,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":24,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margareta Dunn was born in 1596, in Northamptonshire, England. She had at least 1 daughter with William Stevenson. She died in 1624, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1596–1624":"1596–1624","1556–1627":"1556–1627","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1624":"1624","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"enne 28. jaanuari 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13. juuni 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"fi":{"1596–1624":"1596–1624","1556–1627":"1556–1627","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1624":"1624","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"ennen vuotta 28. tammikuuta 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13. kesäkuuta 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England":"Newcastle upon Tyne, Northumberland, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England"},"fr":{"1596–1624":"1596–1624","1556–1627":"1556–1627","1600–1622":"1600–1622","1624":"1624","1622":"1622","1600":"1600","1556":"1556","before 28 January 1600":"avant 28 janvier 1600","1620":"1620","13 June 1622":"13 juin 1622","1596":"1596","1627":"1627","Newcastle 